1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 {This used to be a side line,
but in recent years White scored some successes after this move, so it should
be taken seriously. In my opinion a fairly aggressive play required from Black
to achieve a fully playable position} Bb6 6. Nc3 ({The immediate} 6. Qe2 {
I recommend to meet by} a5 $1 ({Several strong grandmasters opted for} 6... d6
{, which is also playable.}) 7. a4 Nf6 8. Be3 ({After} 8. Nc3 {the position
will transpose to the main line in current game.}) 8... Bxe3 9. Qxe3 Nb4 {
and now White's best move is the awkward} 10. Na3 {after which is clear that
he is not fighting for an advantage anymore. Black can simple castle and start
preparing d7-d5 break.}) 6... Nf6 7. Qe2 {Looks awkward, but White's plan is
very ambitious. He wants to prepare a castling to the queenside. Black is
going to castle to the opposite side of the board. When the kings are on
different flanks - this usually leads to a sharp battle, as each side can push
his pawns forward against the opponent's king, without weakening it's own.} (7.
Bg5 {is an important alternative to take into account. Since black's
dark-squared bishop is far from the kingside, this pin can be annoying for
Black.} h6 8. Bh4 O-O 9. Qe2 {This is the most aggresive option - White is
preparing a long castle.} ({Another possibility would be} 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O d6
11. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd1f3,Ga1e1] The idea behind this move is obvious. White
intends to develop a dangerous initiative by playing moves like f2-f4, Qf3 and
Rae1. Black shouldn't waste time.} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5g6] The maneuver Nc6-e5-g6 is
a typical way to get rid of the pin along the h4-d8 diagonal.} 12. Nd5 g5 13.
Nxb6 axb6 14. Bg3 Ng6 $11 {White has a pair of bishops and black's king is
somewhat weakened. However, black's knights are well placed and he is fully
prepared against white's advance f2-f4. I think that black's position is
perfectly playable and eventually he went on to win in the game 0-1 (68)
Draskovic,L (2454)-Raznikov,D (2507) ICC INT 2015}) 9... a5 10. O-O-O (10. a4 {
will transpose to our game Nataf - Fressinet.}) 10... a4 11. Nd2 Bd4 (11... a3
$6 {is dangerous for Black.} 12. e5 axb2+ 13. Kb1 Nd5 14. Nxd5 Qxh4 15. Ne4 $16
{1-0 (36) Vallejo Pons,F (2695)-Tkachiev,V (2632) Legnica 2013}) 12. Nb5 a3 $1
13. Nc4 $6 (13. Nxa3 $6 Qe7 {[%cal Ga8a3]} 14. Ndc4 Qxe4 $15) (13. bxa3 d6 14.
Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qe3 Nc6 {leads to an unclear position. White has an extra pawn,
but his structure near the king is ruined and the opened "a" file is a source
of worry for White's monarch. He has a pair of bishops, though and the pin
along the diagonal h4-d8 is also a factor. Still, I think that from practical
point of view it's easier to handle this position as Black.}) 13... Bxb2+ 14.
Kb1 d6 15. Nxb2 axb2 16. f4 Bg4 17. Bxf6 Bxe2 18. Bxd8 Bxd1 19. Bxc7 Nb4 $17 {
0-1 (79) Cornette,M (2592)-Tkachiev,V (2637) Nancy 2013}) 7... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]
} 8. a4 (8. e5 {leads to really wild complications. Let's have a look at the
"heavyweight" encounter:} O-O $1 9. exf6 a4 $1 10. Nd5 $1 (10. Nd2 $2 Re8 11.
Nde4 d5 $17) 10... Re8 11. Be3 axb3 12. Qg4 g6 13. Bc4 $1 (13. cxb3 Ba5+ $1)
13... Nb4 $1 14. Nxb4 d5 $1 15. Qf4 dxc4 16. O-O bxc2 17. Nd5 Re6 18. Qxc4 Bxe3
19. fxe3 b5 $1 20. Qc5 Bb7 21. Ne7+ Kh8 22. Qxc2 Raa6 {and Black eliminates
the annoying pawn on f6. This position is balanced. ½-½ (38) Vachier Lagrave,
M (2768)-Carlsen,M (2877) Saint Louis 2014}) 8... O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Nd4 {
This is a key move of our strategy!} 11. Qd3 (11. Nxd4 Bxd4 {is good for Black.
}) 11... Nxb3 12. cxb3 c6 13. O-O-O d5 $1 {That's the point of delaying the
move d7-d6 before. At a price of a pawn Black opens up the center and gets a
good piece play.} 14. exd5 cxd5 15. Nxd5 {In fact, White can't even claim that
he has a healthy extra pawn as it's a doubled one on the "b" file.} g5 $1 16.
Qf3 $1 (16. Bg3 Be6 17. Nxb6 Qxb6 18. Qb5 Qxb5 19. Bxb5 Bxb3 {and White is the
side that will fight for equality here. His bishops are good, but his king is
not safe and the black knight will jump to e4 at some point.}) 16... Nxd5 17.
Rxd5 Qc7+ 18. Bc4 Be6 (18... gxh4 {would lead to a similar perpetual check
after} 19. Qf6 $1 Be6 (19... Qc6 $2 20. Rd6 Qxg2 21. Qg6+ Qxg6 22. Rxg6+ Kh7
23. Rxb6 $16) 20. Rg5+ hxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh7 22. Qh5+ $11) 19. Bxg5 $1 {Leads to
a perpetual check by force.} Bxd5 20. Qxd5 hxg5 21. Qxg5+ Kh8 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23.
Qg6+ Kh8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 {As usually happens, sharp variations usually ended in a
draw Ѕ-Ѕ (24) Nataf,I (2531)-Fressinet,L (2692) Drancy 2016} *

