[Black "Chapter 3: 5.Nxc6 Qf6 6.Qd2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[SourceDate "2017.03.02"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 {This is one of the main
continuations. Now if Black recaptures the knight by the "d" pawn - this will
lead to an unfavourable exchange of queens for him. He will lose the right to
castle and will get doubled pawns on the queenside. Therefore, black's best
reply is intermediate} Qf6 {Threatening a mate in one. When White defends the
pawn on f2, Black will recapture the knight by the "d" pawn, opening the
diagonal for his light-squared bishop and at the same time keeping the queens
on the board.} 6. Qd2 {This move is not so popular. It's main idea is to play
Qf4 at some point. The most common move 6.Qf3 is dealt with in the next
chapters.} (6. f4 dxc6 7. Nc3 Qe7 {I think that this is the best way to
continue the development.} (7... Nh6 $6 8. f5 $1 {Now the sacrifice on f5
doesn't look too promising for Black. Otherwise, the knight on h6 is misplaced.
}) 8. Bd3 Nf6 9. Qf3 Bg4 10. Qg3 O-O-O 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 Qb4 13. O-O (13.
Rb1 $6 {runs into} {[%tqu "En","How should Black continue?","","","f6d5","",10]
} Nd5 $1 14. exd5 Rhe8 15. Be4 cxd5 16. O-O dxe4 $15) 13... Qxb2 14. e5 Nd7 15.
Na4 Qb4 16. Qxa7 Nb6 17. Nxb6+ cxb6 $1 18. a4 Qa5 19. Qxa5 bxa5 $11) (6. Qe2 {
is obstructing the development of the light-squared bishop. After} dxc6 7. Nc3
Be6 8. Be3 {Black has a nice tactical trick:} Ba3 $1 {White is forced to go
back:} 9. Bc1 {and here Black can either repeat moves by 9...Bc5, or play for
a win by 9...Bb4 in an approximately balanced position.}) 6... dxc6 7. Nc3 ({
After} 7. Bd3 {the best way of development for Black is to bring the knight to
g6:} Ne7 8. O-O Ng6 {Later on the knight can go to e5. Now the exchange of
queens is not so good for White:} 9. Qg5 Qxg5 10. Bxg5 f6 11. Bd2 Be6 {
followed by long castling with an excellent piece play for Black.}) ({After} 7.
Qf4 {Black should keep the knight on its' initial square for a while, to
support the queen. Meanwhile, he should develop the queenside by} Be6 8. Bd3
O-O-O {with a comfortable position.}) 7... Bd4 {I recommend this move, though
it looks less natural than the more obvious 7...Ne7 and 7...Be6. Let's try to
figure out, why the move 7.. .Bd4 can be good. At first sight, it doesn't look
logical to move twice with the same piece in the opening. In this position,
however, there are concrete motifs. The alternatives 7...Ne7 and 7...Be6 are
playable, of course. Nevertheless, in case of 7...Ne7, Black has to deal with
the queens exchange offer after 8.Qf4. It is White's dream to exchange queens
and other pieces until only kings and pawns remain. Then he will fully enjoys
his pawns majority on the kingside. In case of 7...Be6 White will harass
black's dark squared bishop by 8.Na4. So, now we can see that the move 7...Bd4
is directed against both white's ideas mentioned above.} 8. Bd3 (8. Bc4 Be6 9.
Bxe6 fxe6 {- opening the "f" file is useful for Black.}) (8. Nd1 Be6 9. Qg5 Qg6
$1 10. f3 f6 {provoking the exchange under favourable conditions.} 11. Qxg6+
hxg6 {Black's kingside rook is already active.} 12. Be3 O-O-O 13. Bxd4 Rxd4 14.
Ne3 Ne7 15. Rd1 c5 16. a3 g5 17. c3 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Ng6 {with a comfortable
play on the dark squares as in the game 0-1 (60) Nataf,I (2553)-Dorfman,J 
(2599) Val d'Isere 2004.}) 8... Ne7 9. O-O Ng6 {A concrete approach to the
position. Black should delay the castle for a while since White is going to
play 10.Kh1 followe by f2-f4. We should bring our knight to e5 before the move
f2-f4.} 10. Kh1 Ne5 11. Be2 (11. f4 Ng4 12. Qe1 Nxh2 $1 13. Kxh2 Qh6+ 14. Kg3
Qg6+ {leads to the same perpetual check that occured in current game.}) 11...
Ng4 12. Nd1 Qd6 13. f4 (13. g3 h5 14. c3 Bb6 {and now the wise decision for
White would be to swap queens by} 15. Qxd6 cxd6 {, but then black's structure
improves and he experiences no problems at all.}) 13... Nxh2 $1 {A small
combination leads to a perpetual check.} 14. Kxh2 Qh6+ 15. Kg3 Qg6+ 16. Kh2
Qh6+ {1/2-1/2 (16) Rublevsky,S (2657)-Onischuk,A (2641) Poikovsky 2002} *

