1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 Qf6 6. Qf3 dxc6 (6... Qxf3
7. gxf3 bxc6 {appeared in hundreds of games. I think that White has hopes for
a slight edge here.}) 7. Bc4 (7. Qxf6 Nxf6 8. f3 Be6 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10. Bd3 Nd7 {
Typical for this line - black's doubled pawns are fully compensated by a good
piece play.} 11. Ke2 Ne5 12. Be3 Bd6 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) Socko,B (2612)-Tkachiev,
V (2624) Tromsoe 2014}) (7. Nd2 Be6 8. Bd3 (8. Nb3 Bb6 $11) 8... O-O-O 9. O-O
Kb8 (9... h5 {is also interesting.}) 10. Qe2 Nh6 11. h3 Rhe8 {All black's
forces are mobilized, so he can be satisfied with the outcome of the opening.})
7... Qe7 {I like this rare move. Normally Black either exchanges queens or
plays 7...Be6 or 7...Ne7. After 7...Qe7 Black wants to develop his knight to
f6 and attack the pawn on e4.} 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Bg5 (9. O-O Be6 10. Bxe6 Qxe6 11.
Bg5 (11. e5 $6 {is not dangerous.} Nd7 12. Ne4 Bb6 {and the e5 pawn will be a
target after Black castles.}) 11... O-O-O 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Rad1 Bd4 14. Rfe1
Rhe8 {Black has clear structural drawbacks on both flanks. However, his pieces
exert pressure on the central lines and his bishop is superior over the knight.
So, Black is not worse here.}) (9. Be3 Bb4 {is okay for Black.}) 9... h6 10.
Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Rd1 $6 ({After} 11. Qxf6 gxf6 {White would not fight for an
advantage, but at least he would be able to keep the balance.}) 11... Qxf3 12.
gxf3 Bd6 $15 {Now white's structure is also worse. The game is now for two
results - either White holds or not. In the game 0-1 (49) Zhou,Y (2470)
-Hovhannisyan,R (2630) London 2016 he did not.} *

