1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 Qf6 6. Qf3 dxc6 7. Nc3 Be6
8. a3 {Ian Nepomniachtchi is one of the biggest specialists in the Scotch for
White. In the current game, he decided to make a waiting, prophylactic move
against a possible idea Bc5-b4. Let's look at the alternatives.} (8. Be3 Bb4 9.
Qxf6 Nxf6 10. f3 Nd7 11. a3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 f6 {[%csl Gc4] Black has no
problems in this endgame. White's pair of strong bishops is neutralized by the
permanent drawbacks in his queenside structure. Later on Black will be able to
bring his knight to c4.}) (8. Qg3 O-O-O 9. Be3 (9. Bg5 $2 Bxf2+) 9... Bxe3 10.
Qxe3 Kb8 11. f4 g5 $5 {I like this pawn sacrifice, employed by an experienced
grandmaster Elizbar Ubilava. Black is fighting for the initiative. In the only
game, that reached this position, White didn't take the pawn, but tried to
grab more space by 12.f5.} (11... Qe7 12. Bd3 Nf6 13. O-O-O Nd7 14. Rhe1 f6 15.
a3 {and White achieved a slight pull in the game ½-½ (40) Nepomniachtchi,I 
(2705)-Fressinet,L (2702) Baku 2015}) 12. f5 (12. fxg5 {is worth to be checked
in practice. I think that after} Qe5 13. Qg3 Qc5 {Black has adequate
compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Bc8 13. Bd3 {and now black's play from the
game ½-½ (40) Kurnosov,I (2577) -Ubilava,E (2544) New Delhi 2008 could be
improved by} Qe7 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 14. Qf2 (14. h4 Bxf5 15. Qxg5 Qxg5 16. hxg5
Be6 $11) 14... Nf6 15. O-O-O Ng4 16. Qg3 Ne5 {Black brought his knight to an
ideal central outpost and can be satisfied with his position.}) 8... O-O-O 9.
Be3 Qe5 10. Bd3 ({In the most recent game on this line Ian tried to develop
his bishop to e2, but it didn't bring him any real benefits after:} 10. Be2 h5
{Typical move for this structure. Black is fighting for space on the kingside.}
11. h4 Bg4 12. Qf4 Qxf4 13. Bxf4 Ne7 14. Bc4 Ng6 15. Bg3 Be6 16. Bxe6+ fxe6 {
Black is at least not worse here. The pawn on h4 could be a target.} 17. Ne2
Rhf8 18. Rf1 Be7 19. Rh1 Bc5 20. Rf1 Be7 ({Black can continue the game with} 
20... Rd7 $5) 21. Rh1 {1/2-1/2 (21) Nepomniachtchi,I (2767)-Andreikin,D (2736)
Wijk aan Zee 2017}) 10... Nf6 11. h3 Nd7 12. Bf4 Qf6 13. Qg3 Bd4 14. O-O (14.
Bxc7 $6 {is not dangerous} Bxf2+ 15. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Kxc7 $15) 14... Be5 {
Black managed to regroup his pieces in an optimal way.} 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. Rad1
g5 $1 {Black got a good control over the dark squares. His position is
slightly preferable and the outcome of the game has nothing to with the
opening - 1-0 (85) Nepomniachtchi,I (2725)-Wang,Y (2730) Danzhou 2016} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scotch: 4...Bc5"]
[Black "Chapter 6: 5.Be3 Qf6 6.c3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "36"]
[SourceDate "2017.03.02"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gf1e2,Ge1g1,
Gf2f4] From a positional point of view, this is White's most logical option.
His idea is to keep the knight in the centre as long as possible. If he has
enough time, White would be happy to complete the development by making moves
like Nc3, Be2, 0-0 and eventually f2-f4. That is why Black should play in a
very energetic way.} Qf6 {Normally, it's not recommended to develop your queen
at such an early stage in the opening. The move 5...Qf6 is very concrete,
attacking the knight. One of the ideas is to provoke the move c2-c3 after
which White's knight couldn't occupy the favorable c3-square. This makes
easier for Black to realize the d7-d5 advance under favorable circumstances.
Black has to bear in mind that if White manages to complete his development
smoothly, his queen will become vulnerable. Therefore, Black's play has to be
concrete enough. He has to take as many benefits as possible from a slight
advantage in development. Remember: every advantage in development is
temporary!} 6. c3 (6. Nb5 {Strange but tricky move.} Bxe3 7. fxe3 Qh4+ $1 {
Black should include this check before going back to d8. Now White's kingside
is also weak.} 8. g3 Qd8 9. Qg4 g5 $5 {The best move! Black is planning to
install his knight on the e5 square.} 10. N1c3 d6 11. Qe2 Ne5 12. Qf2 c6 {
White hasn't got enought compensation for his ruined pawn structure. Black is
slightly better. 0-1 (33) Llaneza Vega,P (2225) -Georgiev,V (2562) La Fere 2012
}) 6... Nge7 {This is the main tabia of the whole line. Currently Black is
ahead in development, but White hopes to catch up soon, keeping more space in
the center. White has many options to develop. In current game we will examine
the side lines.} 7. Nc2 (7. f4 O-O 8. Be2 ({After} 8. e5 $6 Qg6 {White will
have troubles to continue his development. Black keeps an option of ruining
white's center by d7-d6.}) 8... Bxd4 9. cxd4 Qg6 10. Nc3 d5 $1 {This is a
typical way to challenge White's stron pawn centre in this line. Black is
getting a good play on the light squares. In such kind of positions, it is
desirable for Black to exchange the light-squared bishops.Black's pieces are
harmoniously placed.}) (7. Qd2 {White intends to attack the c7-pawn by means
of 8.Nb5. That is why he first defends the e3-bishop. This plan, however, has
serious drawbacks.Being ahead in development, Black manages to create more
than sufficient counterplay.} O-O 8. Nb5 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 d5 $1 {This is the
point! When you are better developed, you should open the centre.} 10. Nxc7 (
10. Nd2 Bd7 {and now again it's not so good for White to grab the pawn on c7:}
11. Nxc7 $6 Rac8 12. Nb5 a6 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. cxd4 Nc6 $15 {
[%csl Rd4,Re4]}) 10... Rb8 11. exd5 Nf5 12. Qe2 Qd8 13. dxc6 Qxc7 14. Nd2 bxc6
15. O-O-O Be6 {with an excellent compensation for the pawn. The opened "b"
file and a clear lag in development is a source of worry for White.}) (7. Bb5 {
The best way to meet this, somewhat weird move is:} O-O 8. O-O Bb6 {Now Black
is ready to meet} 9. f4 {by} Nxd4 10. cxd4 c6 11. Bc4 d5 12. e5 Qh6 13. Bd3 Nf5
14. Bxf5 Bxf5 {with a slight advantage for Black.}) (7. Be2 {is too passive.
After} d5 {Black has a good game.}) 7... Bxe3 8. Nxe3 {The knight is very
useful on e3, but Black is able to carry out the desirable d7-d5 advance
anyway.} Qe5 9. Nd2 d5 {This was the main idea behind black's previous move.
Now Black has an easy development.} 10. Bd3 dxe4 11. Bxe4 Be6 12. Qc2 (12. Qa4
O-O-O 13. Nf3 Qh5 14. O-O f5 15. Bxc6 Nxc6 $11 {Opposite castlings may lead to
a sharp battle, but black's chances are, at least, not worse, as in the
encounter ½-½ (25) Ivanchuk,V (2711) -Anand,V (2786) Monte Carlo 2005}) 12...
O-O-O (12... f5 13. Bxc6+ Nxc6 14. Nf3 Qf6 15. O-O-O Rd8 16. Rxd8+ Kxd8 $1 17.
Rd1+ Kc8 {Black has completed an artifical castling and has a good position.})
13. Nf3 Qb5 {The queen will get here under the pawn kick.} ({I would prefer} 
13... Qh5) 14. b4 Rhe8 15. a4 Qh5 16. O-O f5 17. Bxc6 Nxc6 18. b5 Na5 {In the
forthcoming battle White eventually got the upper hand in the game 1-0 (38)
Morozevich,A (2747) -Georgiev,K (2680) Fuegen 2006, but current position is
still balanced.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scotch: 4...Bc5"]
[Black "Chapter 7: 7.g3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "32"]
[SourceDate "2017.03.02"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. g3 {
White's idea is very logical. By developing his bishop to g2, White makes
difficult for his opponent to execute the d7-d5 advance. Later on, he could
continue grabbing space by means of f2-f4 followed by e4-e5. In order to avoid
this scenario, Black shouldn't waste time. My recommendation is} d5 {The main
and the most logical continuation. As white's bishop is not yet on g2 - this
central thrust is possible and well recommended.} ({For those, looking for an
offbeat line, I can recommend:} 7... h5 $5) 8. Bg2 dxe4 9. O-O {Before staring
active actions, White should complete the development. The alternatives are
not dangerous for Black.} (9. Nb5 Bxe3 10. Nxc7+ Kf8 11. fxe3 (11. O-O $6 Rb8
12. fxe3 Qe5 13. Qb3 f5 14. Nb5 Be6) 11... Rb8 12. Nd5 Qe5 13. Nxe7 Kxe7 {
in both cases with a good position for Black, despite losing the right to
castle. The control over the center is more important.}) (9. Nd2 Bxd4 (9... Bb6
10. Nxe4 Qg6 {is another playable option.}) 10. cxd4 Bf5 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Bxe4
O-O-O {Black is ready either to capture white's central pawn or to block it
safely by Nd5.}) 9... Bxd4 {It is better to exchange this bishop, as it is
most vulnerable piece in black's position.} 10. cxd4 Bf5 11. Nc3 O-O-O {
The other castling is also possible, but here long castling looks more
attractive. The rook immediatly gets to d8 opposite the white queen.} 12. f3 $1
{Emil, as usual, doesn't mind to sacrifice a pawn for the initiative.} (12.
Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe4 Nxd4 14. Qa4 Nec6 {White will have to prove his
compensation. Black has no weaknesses at all.}) 12... exf3 13. Qxf3 Be6 14. Qd1
(14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. Rxf6 {and here Black has a pleasant choice between 15...
Nxd4 and 15...Nf5. In both cases he is, at least, not worse.}) 14... Rxd4 $1 {
The most practical way to defuse White's initiative.} 15. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 16. Qxd4
Nxd4 {Black has two pawns for the exchange and a solid position. The game
Sutovsky,E (2609)-Postny,E (2434) Ramat Aviv/Modiin 2000 eventually ended in a
draw.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Scotch: 4...Bc5"]
[Black "Chapter 8: 7.Bc4 Ne5 8.Bb3"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Annotator "GM Evgeny Postny"]
[PlyCount "46"]
[SourceDate "2017.03.02"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Bc4 {
This is by far White's main move in the position. Having a considerable space
advantage, he is trying to prevent Black's main strategical idea - the d7-d5
pawn break.} Ne5 {This is the most principled reaction. Black wants to chase
White's bishop out of the a2-g8 - diagonal. On the other hand, since the
e5-knight becomes vulnerable, Black should always keep an eye on the ideas
connected with f2-f4.} 8. Bb3 {In this way, White tries to fight against the
advance d7-d5. On the other hand, Black could make use of the fact that the
bishop goes far away from the kingside.} Qg6 {[%csl Re4,Rg2] Double threat. In
fact the threat to one of the pawns is imaginary. Still, it's the best move.}
9. O-O d5 $1 {[%cal Gc8h3] Nevetherless, this move is possible! Note that the
opposition along the g-file is very important in this line.} ({The pawn is
poisonous:} 9... Qxe4 $2 10. Nd2 Qg6 11. f4 Ng4 12. f5 $1 Nxe3 (12... Qh5 $2
13. h3 Nf6 {[%tqu "En","What's the best move for White?","","","d1e1","and the
threat 15.Bd1, trapping the queen can't be parried in a satisfactory way.",10]}
14. Qe1 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gb3d1,Gd1h5] and the threat 15.Bd1, trapping the
queen can't be parried in a satisfactory way.}) 13. fxg6 Nxd1 14. gxf7+ Kf8 15.
Raxd1 $16) 10. Bf4 (10. exd5 $4 {loses much more than just an exchange after}
Bh3 11. g3 Qe4 $19) (10. Nf5 $2 dxe4 $17) (10. f3 dxe4 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nxe4 Bb6
{leads to an approximately equal position.}) 10... Bh3 (10... Qxe4 $6 {is
again dangerous for Black. After} 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gf1e1] he will have troubles
along the "e" file.}) (10... Bg4 {is another possibility.}) 11. Bg3 h5 $1 {
The position is going wild! Black's king is still in the center, but his
pieces are active enough to afford himself such kind of aggressive play.} 12.
Ba4+ (12. gxh3 h4 13. exd5 hxg3 14. fxg3 O-O-O 15. Qe2 Rh5 $44) 12... c6 13.
exd5 h4 (13... Bxg2 {was also an option, eventually leading to approximate
equality after} 14. Kxg2 h4 15. Bc2 f5 16. Re1 hxg3 17. hxg3 Bxd4 18. cxd4 (18.
Qxd4 $4 {[%tqu "En","Find the decisive blow.","","","h8h2","wins a queen.",10]}
Rh2+ $1 {wins a queen.}) 18... Ng4 19. Rh1 O-O-O 20. Nc3 Rxh1 21. Qxh1 Nxd5 $11
) 14. dxc6 (14. Bc2 f5 15. gxh3 hxg3 16. fxg3 O-O-O 17. Qe2 Rxd5 {with
sufficient play for the pawn.}) 14... N5xc6 15. gxh3 hxg3 16. hxg3 Rxh3 17. Kg2
Qh6 18. Bxc6+ bxc6 19. Rh1 Rxh1 20. Qxh1 Qxh1+ 21. Kxh1 Rd8 22. Kg2 Bxd4 23.
cxd4 Rxd4 {The dust has settled and players reached an equal endgame. Draw was
agreed few moves later in the game ½-½ (27) Piorun,K (2681)-Inarkiev,E (2686)
Gjakova 2016.} *

