1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Bc4 Ne5 8.
Be2 {This is the main line. White is making a step backward but in the future
he will be trying to prove that the e5-knight is unstable. On the other hand,
we shoud point out that this central knight creates a lot of dynamic
possibilities.} d6 {In this case, I recommend the solid option.} 9. O-O ({
The immediate} 9. f4 {fails to pose any problems. After the sequence,} Ng4 $1
10. Bxg4 Qh4+ 11. Bf2 Qxg4 12. Qxg4 Bxg4 {Black has no problems in this
endgame. White's attempt to trap the light-squared bishop by} 13. f5 {also
doesn't yield him any advantage in view of} Bh5 $1 {The bishop will have a
safe square on f7. For instanse:} 14. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4]} f6 15. Ne6 {Looks
marvellous for White to get the knight on such a powerful outpost. However,
after} Bxf2+ 16. Kxf2 Kd7 17. Nxg7 Bf7 18. g4 Rhg8 19. Nh5 Bxh5 20. gxh5 Rg5 {
Black wins back the pawn and can already think about more than equality.}) 9...
Qg6 {The usual square for the black queen in this line.} 10. Kh1 ({The
somewhat passive} 10. Nd2 $6 Bh3 11. Bf3 O-O 12. Kh1 Nxf3 13. Qxf3 Bd7 {
is absolutely fine for Black. His pair of bishops is a factor. Later he can
consider opening up the position by f7-f5.}) ({We should always consider the
aggressive} 10. f4 {In this case, however, Black is doing more than ok after}
Qxe4 11. Bf2 Bxd4 12. cxd4 N5g6 {[%csl Rf4]} 13. g3 Bh3 14. Bf3 Qf5 15. Re1 (
15. Bxb7 $2 Rb8 16. Bg2 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 h5 $1 $17) 15... d5 16. Qb3 O-O 17. Nc3
Bg4 18. Bxd5 Nxd5 {1/2-1/2 (18) Nakamura,H (2735)-Grischuk,A (2733) Ohrid 2009}
) ({The solid approach based on 10.f3 and 11.Nd2 allows Black to execute the
d7-d5 break in a comfortable redaction.} 10. f3 O-O 11. Nd2 d5 {Black has
already equalized. A typical line would be} 12. Kh1 dxe4 13. fxe4 Bg4 14. Bf4
Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Bd6 16. Nb5 N7c6 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 (17... cxd6 {is also okay.}) 18.
Nc4 Qe6 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Qb5 c5 $1 21. Qxb7 (21. Qxc5 Nd3 $11) 21... Nd3 $11)
10... Qxe4 {Now Black can take this pawn. White has too many bishops along the
"e" file, so can't cause any real troubles.} 11. Nd2 Qg6 12. Nb5 ({After} 12.
f4 $6 Bxd4 $1 (12... Ng4 $6 13. f5 $1 {leads to unnecessary complications,
which might be in white's favour.}) 13. Bxd4 N5c6 {white's compensation for
the pawn is not sufficient.}) 12... O-O {Black is forced to give the pawn on
c7, but it's not a big deal.} ({Don't even think about a move such as} 12...
Kd8 $4 {After} 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. Nc4+ Nd7 15. Re1 {the position is just lost
for Black due to uncastled king and a total loss of coordination.}) 13. Nxc7
Rb8 14. Bh5 (14. Nc4 Nxc4 (14... b6 {is also okay for Black.}) 15. Bxc4 Bxe3
16. fxe3 Bf5 {is equal, as in the game ½-½ (32) Rublevsky,S (2665)-Svidler,P
(2690) Maikop 1998}) 14... Qf5 15. f4 $6 (15. Qe2 Bxe3 16. fxe3 Qc2 17. Nb3
Qxe2 18. Bxe2 {Both sides have weak pawns in this position. Black is, perhaps,
slightly better thanks to the great knight on e5.}) 15... Ng4 $6 (15... Bxe3 $2
16. fxe5 Qxe5 17. Nc4 Qc5 18. Nxe3 Qxe3 19. Re1 Qg5 20. Qxd6 Qxh5 21. Rxe7 $14
{is what is hoping for.}) (15... N5g6 $1 {is the best response, as appeared in
a couple of correspondence games. Black is even much better here as White has
problems to bring back his knight from c7.}) 16. Bxg4 Qxg4 17. Nc4 Qd7 18. Bxc5
dxc5 19. Qxd7 Bxd7 20. Rad1 Bg4 21. Rde1 Nc6 22. f5 {White is pressing. This
is the blitz encounter ½-½ (70) Kasparov,G (2812)-Nakamura,H (2787) Saint
Louis 2016} *

