{Black has a choice between a few moves here. Do you remember which is the
main move in our repertoire?} 7... Bd4 $1 {I recommend this move, though it
looks less natural than the more obvious 7...Ne7 and 7...Be6. Let's try to
figure out, why the move 7...Bd4 can be good. At first sight it doesn't look
logical to move twice with the same piece in the opening, however, there are
concrete motifs in the position. The alternatives 7...Ne7 and 7...Be6 are
playable, of course. However, in a case of 7...Ne7 Black has to deal with a
queens exchange offer after 8.Qf4. It is white's dream to exchange queens and
other pieces until only kings and pawns remain. Then he will fully enjoy his
pawns majority on the kingside. In a case of 7...Be6 White will harass black's
dark squared bishop by 8.Na4. So, now we can see that the move 7...Bd4 is
directed against both white's ideas mentioned above.} 8. Bd3 Ne7 9. O-O Ng6 {
[%emt 0:00:03] Black has a good game.} *

